-- Japan, Malaysia, S. Korea, Taiwan, Thailand: Asian Bond, Currency Previews
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-07-04T21:45:58Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-04/japan-malaysia-s-korea-taiwan-thailand-asian-bond-currency-previews.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold a
media briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.095 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 87.72 per dollar at 6:37 a.m. in Sydney.  
 Malaysia: The central bank will sell 1.5 billion ringgit
($464 million) of 58-day notes today. It will also sell 1
billion ringgit of 58-day Islamic notes.  
 Trade data released late on July 2 showed exports increased
21.9 percent from a year earlier in May, following a 26.6
percent gain the previous month. The median forecast of
economists surveyed by Bloomberg was for growth of 26.6 percent
in May.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent debt maturing in November
2019 was 3.93 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit
was at 3.225.  
 South Korea: The government will sell 1.1 trillion won
($897 million) of three-year bonds today. The central bank will
sell 1 trillion won of 91-day notes, 2 trillion won of 28-day
debt and 300 billion won of 182-day securities.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.38 percent. The won was at 1,228.75.  
 Thailand: The government will sell 2 billion baht ($62
million) of 28-day bills, 4 billion baht of 91-day bills and 4
billion baht of 182-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in December
2019 was 3.26 percent. The baht was at 32.41.  
 Taiwan: Consumer prices climbed 1.01 percent in June from a
year earlier, after a 0.74 percent increase in May, according to
the median estimate in a Bloomberg survey of economists before a
government report today.  
 The yield on the government’s 1.375 percent note maturing
in March 2020 was 1.41 percent, according to Gretai Securities
Market, the island’s biggest exchange for bonds. The Taiwan
dollar traded at NT$32.278.  
 Singapore: The government will sell S$3.6 billion ($2.6
billion) of 91-day treasury bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent note due September 2020 was
2.36 percent, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The local
dollar was at S$1.3913.  
